Productivity of knowledge workers cannot be measured.
>We do not know how to measure the [productivity] of [knowledge workers] and the [self-actualization] of knowledge workers. But we do know a great deal about how to improve both ([Drucker], "[The Practicing Manager]").

>If we do not increase the productivity of knowledge workers, we will have the economic stress of [inflationary pressure] and the social disease of [alienation]. We cannot measure the productivity or self-actualization of knowledge workers. But we do know how to make them productive and self-actualized.

